proper expansion of these terms would result in terms, \textit{e.g.} in the electron's case,  
%
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{y} \supset \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \, y^e_{diag} \; v \left( \overline{e_L} e_R + \overline{e_R} e_L \right) + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} y^e_{diag} h(x) \left( \overline{e_L} e_R + \overline{e_R} e_L \right) \quad , 
\label{electron mass}
\end{equation}
%
This clearly translates to the first terms in (\ref{electron mass}) equating to a mass term, $m_e = \frac{y^e v}{\sqrt{2}} $, while the second terms represent interaction coupling between the electron and the Higgs boson.  
%
This is how the Higgs mechanism generates the mass to all of the fermionic and leptonic sector except neutrinos, due to the SM not containing right handed neutrinos.  % Now it is beneficial to write the mass terms as matricial form as,

{ \color{gray} The lack of a right handed neutrinos is very commonly addressed in most BSM scenarios. } 

\begin{comment}
Generically we can write the mass terms for all fermions as,
\begin{equation}
M^u_{ij} = Y^u_{ij} \frac{v}{\sqrt{2}} \quad M^d_{ij} = Y^d_{ij} \frac{v}{\sqrt{2}} \quad M^e_{ij} = Y^e_{ij} \frac{v}{\sqrt{2}}
\end{equation}
\end{comment}

The diagonalization of the Yukawa matrices is a simple eigenvalue problem, however note the Yukawa matrices remain arbitrary to some extent.
%
The Yukawa matrices contain some parameters that are not observable, and thus are not physical parameters, since they can be absorbed by redefinitions of the real fermion fields i.e. there are several combinations of $Y^{u,d}$ that return the same mass spectrum. 

Note that the increasing masses seen in each generation depend directly on the term hierarchy of the Yukawa terms. This means that the mass of all particles directly relate to how strongly they each interacts with the Higgs boson.

If you then take into account the real masses e.g. for the leptons, you'd note that the tau mass is in the GeV range while the electron's is in the 0.1 MeV range. These translate to very different couplings for each flavour. 

\subsubsection{Physical parameters}

The analysis of Quarks is a bit trickier and will require the introduction of the quark mixing trough the Cabibbo-Kobayashi-Maskawa (CKM) matrix. 

But before moving onto it, it is relevant to take a small detour to introduce what is a physical parameter. Physical parameters are parameters that cannot be rotated away by performing phase transformations or flavour rotations. For the example we introduced above in, Eq.\,\ref{electron mass}, the charged lepton yukawa matrix can always be made real and positive through a bi-unitarity transformation, as,
% 
\begin{equation}
Y_l \rightarrow U_L Y_l U_R = \hat{Y}_l = diag(y_e,y_\mu,y_\tau )
\end{equation}
%
To count the physical parameters of the Yukawa matrix, one starts by noting the initial parameters of $Y_l$, 9 real and 9 complex. Secondly in the unitary matrices you can find $2\times(3 \ \text{real} + 6 \ \text{im.} )$. Given their hermitian nature, you can rotate both unitarity matrices by a phase without any consequence, so we have 3 imaginary parameters without effect. To sum up, we have $9 - 2 \times 3 = 3 $ real and $ 9 - ( 2 \times 6 - 3 )$ imaginary physical parameters. The three real physical parameters are clearly the charged lepton masses. 

% If you try to count the physical parameters of the Yukawa matrix, you can see that initialy you have $Y_l$ with 9 real and 9 complex paramaters. And in the unitary matrices you can find $2\times(3 \ \text{real} + 6 \ \text{im.} )$.

%And seeing that if we rotate both unitarity matrices by a phase there is no change to the Yukawa values, so there are 3 imaginary parameters without effect. To sum up we have $9 - 2 \times 3 = 3 $ real and $ 9 - ( 2 \times 6 - 3 )$ imaginary physical paramaters. The three real physical parameters are the charged lepton masses, while there are no physical phases. 

